<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Russians Demand Resident Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ethnic Russians Demand Resident Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0205145994 Tallinn BNS in English 1350 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0205145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, 2 May, BNS -- Mainly elderly residents 
from northeast Estonia's Russian-populated cities of Narva and 
Sillamae formed a human chain on the Tallinn-St. Petersburg 
highway Sunday [1 May], demanding permanent resident's status 
and higher pensions. 
  The picketers demanded the authorities to grant a permanent 
resident's status to everybody who has the Estonian resident's 
status stamp in their Soviet passports from earlier than July 
1990, said Nikolai Klotschkov, editor in chief of Sillamae's 
local newspaper. 
  Other demands included amendments to the pension law, 
determining of the cost of living index, and increasing the 
pensions of retired workers of the nuclear industry -- the 
leading branch for decades under the Soviet rule in the once 
closed-for-outsiders military plant town of Sillamae. 
  The roadside picket, organized by local pensioners unions, 
was called by the activists a "Baltic Chain", referring to the 
23 Aug 1989, event under the same name. 
  In 1989, Estonians, Latvians and Lithuanians linked their 
hands in a chain extending from Tallinn to Vilnuis to demand 
from the then Soviet leadership official denouncement of the 
1939 Molotov-Ribbentrop pact. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

