<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greece To Support Nuclear Plant Pending Assurances </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greece To Support Nuclear Plant Pending Assurances </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0305150694 Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1300 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0305150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1300 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Armenian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Armenian Prime Minister Grant Bagratyan sent a 
letter to Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou in February 
this year asking him to support the Armenian Government's 
request for financial assistance from the EU to reopen the 
Armenian nuclear plant. 
  In his reply, the Greek prime minister gave assurances that 
he will spare no effort in supporting the request of the 
Armenian Government, but at the same time he expressed the 
following view: Considering that most of the EU countries are 
concerned about safety in connection with the Armenian nuclear 
plant, Armenia needs to completely convince the international 
community that the opening of the nuclear plant will in no way 
pose a danger. 
  I want to reiterate the Greek Government's determination to 
actively contribute to your country's economic reforms and 
democratic processes to which you and the friendly Armenian 
people remain dedicated, wrote Greek Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou at the end of his letter. 

</TEXT>

