<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Humanitarian Aid Not Reaching Destination </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Humanitarian Aid Not Reaching Destination </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0405110094 Tbilisi SVOBODNAYA GRUZIYA in Russian 28 Apr 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> AU0405110094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi SVOBODNAYA GRUZIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["BS-Press" report under rubric "According to Reports From </F>
Correspondents and Information Agencies": "According to 
Information From the Chamber of Control, a Large Part of 
Humanitarian Aid Is Not Reaching Its Destination"] 
  [Text] Referring to violations connected with receiving 
and distributing humanitarian aid, Revaz Shavishvili, chairman 
of the Chamber of Control, stated today in an interview given to 
the "Alioni" [television] program that the Chamber of Control 
has simply confirmed something that was already known to the 
population. According to Shavishvili, a significant part of 
humanitarian aid given by countries to Georgia in the form of 
medicines and food products either does not leave the warehouse 
for a long period of time or, after being allocated its place of 
destination, ends up in the hands of commercial structures. As 
an example, he mentioned 58,000 ampules of insulin and two dozen 
tonnes of cheese that could no longer be used as their 
consumption date had expired. 
  Shavishvili also pointed out that, despite a multitude of 
similar facts exposed by the Chamber of Control during the 
course of recent checks, they still do not reflect the real 
state of affairs. Shavishvili believes the reason for such chaos 
lies in the lack of a single coordination center for the 
distribution of humanitarian aid. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

