Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Bank Chief Expresses Concern for Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Bank Chief Expresses Concern for Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0305193694 Yerevan SNARK in English 1155 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0305193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan SNARK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tbilisi, 3 May (SNARK)--Georgia spends 10 times more 
than allows the state of her economy, stated today the President 
of Georgian National Bank, Nodar Djavakhishvili, to the SNARK 
newsman. In his opinion, the introduction of a new national 
currency, lari, is now highly questionable, since even a small 
stabilization of Georgian coupon is impossible. 
  "It is impossible to exist on account of emission. We 
increase every quarter the money issue which is not secured by 
the real content, thus subjecting the people to 
hyper-inflation", said Djavakhishvili. He observed that 
"Georgian economy doesn't even compensate its expenses for gas". 
  "If so, then we should not use gas at all. By the way, 
nearly 80 percent of Georgian population actually do not use 
gas. Only Tbilisi, Rustavi, Batumi and Kutaissi receive gas", 
noted the head banker of Georgia. He also suggested that the 
Georgian Government would finally make a decision: "In the case 
Georgia goes towards the ruble zone, rather than strengthens its 
coupon, the government needs a new chairman of the National 
Bank", said Djavakhishvili. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

