<H3> <TI>   Parliament Adopts Draft on Storage, Disposal of KGB Files </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Adopts Draft on Storage, Disposal of KGB Files </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0405073794 Tallinn BNS in English 1944 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0405073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, 3 May, BNS -- The Latvian Saeima (parliament) 
Legal Committee passed for the second reading in plenary session 
a draft law on storage and disposal of Soviet security service 
archives. 
  The committee wants the bill to be considered on Thursday [5 
May], said its head Aivars Endzins. 
  After the third reading, the law could take effect 27 or 28 
May, Endzins prognosticated. 
  The law would be used to test the alleged KGB collaboration 
of five MPs, among them Foreign Minister Georgs Andrejevs and 
Minister for Special Tasks Edvins Inkens. 
  The committee supplemented the bill with rights for defense 
lawyer and the order of appeal. 
  If the court finds that the deputies were KGB operatives, 
their mandates will be nullified and the ruling can be regarded 
as basis to break work or service relations. 
  The fact that the deputies were mentioned in KGB files alone 
does not testify about their collaboration because information 
on results of cooperation is lacking. 

</TEXT>

