<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernobyl, Nuclear Safety Discussed With G-7 Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernobyl, Nuclear Safety Discussed With G-7 Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305172094 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1600 
GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [No video available] </F>
  [Text] A meeting between representatives of the Ukrainian 
Government and a delegation from the G-7 countries was held 
today in the Cabinet of Ministers. The Ukrainian Government 
group was headed by Deputy Prime Minister Valeriy Shmarov and 
the delegation from the G-7 countries by Antonio Puri Purini, 
authorized minister and head of the seventh department's working 
group on nuclear safety. This meeting was of a consultative 
nature, dealing mostly with issues of nuclear safety in Ukraine. 
They discussed cooperation by donor countries of the fund for 
nuclear safety, the EBRD, and other influential international 
organizations with Ukraine in technical, economic, and financial 
aspects. The sides, therefore, expressed readiness for joint 
action in the area of the safe exploitation of atomic energy and 
improving the state of the environment. 
  However, the word Chernobyl was often heard because one of 
the main conditions for all-round help from the G-7 countries to 
Ukraine is not only in resolving the problems of nuclear safety 
but also in strengthening the economy and the gradual closure of 
the Chernobyl AES [nuclear electric power station] generating 
sets. 

</TEXT>

