<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Hold Talks on Nagorno-Karabakh in Bishkek </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Hold Talks on Nagorno-Karabakh in Bishkek </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Participants Discuss Cease-Fire </H4>

<F P=102> LD0405163194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1503 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Today participants in a meeting on Nagorno-Karabakh 
opened in Bishkek on May 4 at the initiative of the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly started to discuss a protocol on a 
cease-fire in the zone of the Armenian-Azeri conflict. As 
Interfax learned from well-informed sources in the Kyrgyz 
capital, the cease-fire is planned for May 9, 1994. 
  The meeting is attended by Chairman of the Armenian 
parliament Babken Ararktsyan, Deputy Chairman of the Azeri 
Milli-Mejlis Afiyaddin Dzhalilov, Acting Chairman of the 
Karabakh parliament Karen Baburyan, and mediators Chairman of 
the CIS Interparliamentary Assembly and the Russian Council of 
Federation Vladimir Shumeyko and Chairman of the Kyrgyz 
parliament Medetkan Sherimkulov. 
  As Sherimkulov told Interfax during a break that the talks 
were difficult and their results unknown. At the same time, he 
expressed hope that on Wednesday the sides will agree to sign 
the protocol. 
  As a well-informed source in the Azeri presidential 
administration told Interfax, Chairman of the Azeri parliament 
Rasul Guliyev failed to arrive in Bishkek due to the aggravation 
of the situation in the zone of the Karabakh conflict. The 
source said that Guliyev has been in the front line zone in the 
past few days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

