<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Hold Talks on Nagorno-Karabakh in Bishkek </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Hold Talks on Nagorno-Karabakh in Bishkek </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Latent Tension' Mars Bishkek Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> LD0405150194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1346 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by KYRGYZKABAR correspondent Albert Bogdanov for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Bishkek, 4 May -- The talks on ways to settle the 
Azerbaijani-Armenian conflict in Nagorno-Karabakh began today in 
Kyrgyzstan's capital in the atmosphere of latent tension. The 
sides were ready to take issue on any minor point. Since 
Nagorno-Karabakh representatives were absent from the reception 
staged by President Askar Akayev before the start of the talks 
and its delegation did not get an opportunity to state its 
position at the morning session, one can understand the harsh 
assessment of the conference from Karen Baburyan, acting 
chairman of Armenia's Supreme Soviet, who said: "It could not be 
worse. If they make some decisions without Nagorno-Karabakh, 
all right, let them. But who then is to return the conquered 
territories?" 
  The first to speak was deputy chairman of Azerbaijan's 
Supreme Soviet Afiyaddin Dzhalilov, who categorically demanded 
an immediate cease-fire and the withdrawal of troops from the 
occupied territories. 
  The Armenian side reacted negatively to the fact that the 
chairman of Azerbaijan's Supreme Soviet did not turn up and that 
the meeting was attended by his deputy instead. [Armenian] 
Parliament Speaker Babken Ararktsyan stated in no uncertain 
terms that this strongly undermined the authority of the present 
meeting. He said it is hard to understand why Azerbaijan has 
not accepted measures proposed by Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh 
to settle the conflict, even though it is to receive territories 
in return. He reiterated the words of President Levon 
Ter-Petrosyan, contained in his message to the participants in 
the talks, to the effect that the sides' frequently repeated 
statements about peace do not bring peace and quiet to the area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

