<DOCNO> FBIS4-61199 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov087cc_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Hold Talks on Nagorno-Karabakh in Bishkek </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Hold Talks on Nagorno-Karabakh in Bishkek </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    CIS Deputies Discuss Karabakh Problem </H4>

<F P=102> LD0505090194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0727 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS Correspondent Boris Mainayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek May 5 TASS -- Parliamentarians from Russia, 
Azerbaijan, Armenia and Kyrgyzstan and representatives of 
Nagorno-Karabakh worked late into the night on Wednesday [4 May] 
and resumed discussions early on Thursday morning to try and 
find a way around the stumbling block which, according to the 
leader of the Armenian parliamentary commission on 
Nagorno-Karabakh, Seiran Bagdasaryan, is formed by Azerbaijan's 
state policy rejecting the introduction of CIS peace-keepers and 
CSCE observers to the Karabakh region. 
  According to Bagdasaryan, Azerbaijan has not made up its 
mind 
concerning the main question about the disengagement of the 
warring forces. Only after the guns become silent, will it be 
possible to begin peace talks, bring back the refugees and 
exchange hostages. Azerbaijan is proposing a simple lull, but 
the situation is calling for the beginning of a lengthy process 
which can guarantee the non-resumption of combat activities, 
Bagdasaryan said. 
  Different variants of stationing peace-keeping forces have 
been proposed. In April the Azeri leader, President Heydar 
Aliyev refused to sign the resolution on the sending of CIS 
troops to the region approved by the CIS summit. At present the 
Azeri delegation is dragging feet in order not to sign a simple 
protocol, containing a call on the heads of state and 
parliaments to from CIS peace-keeping contingent and begin a 
peaceful dialogue. This is a practical attempt at hiding behind 
verbiage about Azerbaijan's sovereignty in an effort to avoid 
any solution to the Karabakh problem, Bagdasaryan said. 
  The Azers are again trying to use these talks in order to 
play for time, while they are preparing their troops for new 
offensive, the Armenian parliamentarian said. Political 
realities are now such that Azerbaijan will have to recognise 
Nagorno-Karabakh's independence. Policy can no longer be build 
on quantitative indices of the sort that there are seven million 
of Azers and only 150 thousand of Karabakh people. World 
experience shows that this is by far not the most decisive 
factor, Bagdasaryan said. He stressed his confidence that 
Azerbaijan would have to recognise Karabakh's independence 
earlier or later. 
  As concerns talks as a whole, Bagdasaryan said they are 
necessary because they help CIS parliamentarians to know each 
other better, clarify their respective positions and make steps 
towards peace. Meetings of this kind also help strengthen the 
CIS inter-parliamentary assembly, which is a promising process," 
the Armenian envoy said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

