<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baltic Presidents Hold Talks in Latvia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Baltic Presidents Hold Talks in Latvia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hope for Prompt Russian Withdrawal </H4>

<F P=102> LD0405131294 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1200 GMT 4 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>
<F P=105>  Latvian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At President Guntis Ulmanis' initiative, Estonian 
State President Lennart Meri and Lithuanian State President 
Algirdas Brazauskas came to his residence in Jurmala yesterday. 
The meeting was private. The presidents discussed the internal 
situation in the Baltic states and foreign policy issues. No 
documents were adopted. All three presidents agreed not to make 
a statement for the press. However, respecting the specific 
character of reporters' work, the president of our country 
[Latvia] decided to hold a small news conference. 
  Guntis Ulmanis said at Maikapara House today that the 
agreements signed between Latvia and Russia were discussed 
during the presidents' meeting. All the presidents of the 
Baltic states expressed the hope that the agreements concluded 
between Latvia and Russia would speed up the Russian Army 
withdrawal from Estonia. Ulmanis noted that a regular round of 
talks was held in Tallinn today. 
  The presidents of Latvia, Lithuania, and Estonia also 
discussed cooperation with those countries which expressed 
support for the agreements signed between Latvia and Russia. 
The agreements concluded have an important role in the 
stabilization of the Baltic states. The presidents expressed 
hope that Western countries which supported the process of 
drafting the agreements will continue to watch how they are 
implemented. 
  This evening at the president's residence, Guntis Ulmanis 
will meet ambassadors accredited in Latvia. 

</TEXT>

