<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 5 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 5 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505051294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0433 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505051294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 5 ITAR-TASS -- Russia's national 
newspapers today lead with reports about the agreement on 
Palestinian autonomy in Gaza and Jericho signed in Cairo on 
Wednesday by Palestine Liberation Organisation leader Yasir 
'Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA comments: "This agreement is the first 
and most significant step along the path of implementation of 
the Washington declaration of principles". The newspaper quotes 
Yasir 'Arafat as saying this event signifies peace not only for 
Israel and not only for the entire Arab world, but for mankind 
as a whole. 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA stressed that "the document signed in Cairo 
yesterday marks the creation of the first-ever Palestinian 
autonomy and opens a new chapter in the settlement of the 
Arab-Israeli chapter. Along with this, the Palestinians in the 
Gaza Strip are vieweing their autonomy with apprehension. Much 
will depend on the ability of the new authorities to improve the 
desperate situation of the local inhabitants, the overwhelming 
majority of whom live in abject poverty". 
  Russian Minister of Foreign Affairs Andrey Kozyrev, who is 
in 
Cairo in connection with the signing of the agreement on the 
Palestinian autonomy, told the newspaper TRUD that "the 
agreement on Gaza and Jericho is the first major step towards 
durable peace in the region, it marks a historic reconciliation 
between Israel and its Palestinian neighbours, I hope it will 
stimulate progress along other lines of the Middle East 
settlement. The Israeli-Palestinian agreement must be followed 
by its practical implementation. This will be a stage no less 
important than the negotiations". 
  KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA said in its comment on the signing: 
"Both Rabin and 'Arafat are in a hurry to sign peace today, not 
tomorrow. If they failed to do so, the right-wingers would 
certainly come to power at the next elections in Israel, and 
their understanding of the word "peace" is quite different. 
'Arafat's political career is also at stake -- should his 
policy fail, the irreplaceable PLO leader would be replaced by 
his irreconcilable opponents". 
  KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA noted in this respect that "literally a 
few hours before the signing, Tel Aviv raised, without any 
preliminary notice, 25 new disputable questions. But 
nonetheless 'Arafat and Rabin, unshakable in their desire for 
peace, sealed the historic document with the signatures by their 
own hands". 
  KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA carries an interview with Yabloko 
[Yavlinskiy Bloc] leader Grigory Yavlinskiy. Asked why his 
faction was against the political amnesty, which set President 
Yeltsin's arch-rivals free, Yavlinskiy said: "We voted against 
because we thought it most important to set up a commission for 
the investigation for the tragic events of October 3 and 4. It 
would have inevitably made clear that both sides were to blame 
for the bloodshed. But the right-wingers and left-wingers 
agreed on a compromise which set them free from moral 
condemnation and juridical liability. I am convinced that the 
question remains. Life itself will put it on our agenda". 
  PRAVDA also takes up the subject placing a statement by 
General Valentin Varennikov on its front page who objects 
against the application of the political amnesty to himself. 
Varennikov writes "I have no objections to the State Duma 
decision on amnesty. But I repeat yet again that throughout all 
stages of the preliminary investigation and during the court 
trial I never acknowledged and do not acknowledge now the 
accusations against myself. I declared and declare myself again 
not guilty." 
  Valentin Varennikov said he had appealed to the military 
collegium of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation to 
institute criminal proceedings against the people guilty of the 
break-up of the Soviet Union. The text of his letter of appeal 
is also printed in the newspaper SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA. The same 
newspaper publishes reports about marches and rallies on May 
first. 
  ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI carries an interview between the 
newspaper's editor in chief and the chief of the presidential 
apparatus, Federal Minister Vladimir Kvasov, who comments on 
lobbying government decisions. "This country has yet to create 
the institute of lobbyism. And I am sure that it will be 
created. Such institutes exist in all market economies". 
  Economy Minister Aleksandr Shokhin reports in ROSSIYSKIYE 
VESTI about the results of the Russian delegation's 
participation in the recent session of the leading bodies of the 
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank, as well as the 
conference of the finance ministers and central bank governors 
of the Group of Seven countries. Aleksandr Shokhin expressed 
satisfaction with the results of encounters in Washington, he 
noted among other things that "an agreement on a 70 million 
dollar loan to Russia was signed with the World Bank to develop 
the employment and social insurance services". 

</TEXT>

