<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Khasbulatov Does Not Plan Return to Politics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Khasbulatov Does Not Plan Return to Politics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505090894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0825 
GMT 5 May 95 </F>

<F P=103> LD0505090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sharip Asuyev] </F>
  [Text] Groznyy, 5 May -- "Rumors regarding Ruslan 
Khasbulatov's political activities are very much exaggerated." 
That is how Ruslan Khasbulatov's close relative, who wishes to 
remain anonymous, commented on a rumor in the press alleging 
that the former chairman of the Russian parliament has virtually 
headed the opposition in Chechnya. In a conversation with an 
ITAR-TASS correspondent, he admitted that Ruslan Khasbulatov has 
frequent meetings with his compatriots, but "these meetings are 
always held at the request of the residents themselves and they 
practically do not touch on Chechnya's domestic political 
problems." 
  An ITAR-TASS correspondent did not succeed in meeting Ruslan 
Khasbulatov himself. The former chairman avoids journalists or 
answers with one and the same phrase: "I have come to Groznyy to 
meet relatives and have a rest." 
  According to information from Ruslan Khasbulatov's immediate 
entourage, he is preparing to resume not his political but his 
scientific activities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

