<H3> <TI>   Defendant in 1991 Coup Attempt Rejects Amnesty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defendant in 1991 Coup Attempt Rejects Amnesty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405141394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1304 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] One of the defendants in the trial of members of the 
1991 abortive coup in Moscow, Valentin Varennikov, (formerly, 
deputy Soviet defence minister) has said he did not want the 
amnesty declared by parliament in February to be applied to 
himself. Varennikov has appealed to Russia's High Court for 
further hearings into his own case, his lawyer Dmitriy 
Shteynberg told Interfax. 
  Varennikov reasons that he wants those responsible for 
wrecking of the former Soviet Union to be found out, something 
that can only be done during court hearings, he believes. 

</TEXT>

