<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kaliningrad Duma Inaugurates Work, Elects Speaker </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kaliningrad Duma Inaugurates Work, Elects Speaker </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0405140794 Kaliningrad KALININGRADSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 
28 Apr 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> WS0405140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kaliningrad KALININGRADSKAYA PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by N. Borovskaya: "Speaker Was Elected on the First </F>
Day"] 
  [Text] The Kaliningrad Oblast Duma began its work on 26 
April. The agenda prepared by the organizing committee included 
16 issues. Naturally, deputies were unable to cope with such a 
number of topics in just one day, all the more so since a 
portion of the first session was devoted to representative 
issues. Members of political parties and civil movements 
welcomed the representative body and expressed their 
expectations toward it. 
  Later, deputies arrived in the suite on 17 Kirov Street -- 
which had been previously allotted to them -- to begin their 
work. Gennadiy Batutin, the oldest deputy of the Duma, was 
elected the chairman of the first session. Deputy Danuta 
Smirnova was elected his deputy. Yuriy Matochkin, head of the 
Kaliningrad Oblast Administration, addressed the Oblast Duma. 
  During the first day, deputies managed to form working 
bodies 
and approve the statute of the first session. The most urgent 
question -- who would become the Duma speaker and deputy speaker 
-- was resolved within five hours. In the course of several 
rounds of voting and numerous consultations, Valeriy 
Nikolayevich Ustyugov, head of the Baltiysk Rayon 
Administration, was elected Duma speaker by a margin of 17 
votes. Yuriy Nikolayevich Semenov was elected deputy speaker 
(13 votes cast in favor, 6 against, and one invalid). 
  We will provide more details on this fascinating story, as 
well as on the entire session that lasted two days, in the 
following issues of our newspaper. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

