<H3> <TI>   Kebich Accused of Usurping Radio, TV in Campaign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kebich Accused of Usurping Radio, TV in Campaign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405150294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1402 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405150294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 85 (575); </F>
compiled by Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by 
Vladimir Shishlin] 
  [Text] Prime Minister Vyacheslav Kebich's campaign officers 
have succeeded to collect signatures of more than 100,000 voters 
and 150 deputies, which is more than is needed to stand as 
presidential candidate. The Central Electoral Commission [CEC] 
is due to register him as such in the next few days. 
  Kebich is free to choose whether he wants to be nominated by 
parliament or the voters, a CEC source told INTERFAX IF Note: 
Under the election law, a presidential candidate is expected to 
collect 100,000 signatures on the ground or 70 signatures by 
Belarussian deputies to qualify for the race. As many as 19 
candidates seek nomination in a signature collecting campaign 
due to end on May 14. 
  Many of the contenders are about to collect the required 
number of signatures. Among those collecting 70,000 signatures 
are former Speaker Stanislav Shushkevich, Communist Party and 
People's Front Movement leaders Vasiliy Novikov and Zenon 
Pozniak as well as head of the now-abolished anti-corruption 
commission Aleksandr Likhashenko. 
  Critics of the Prime Minister have accused him of usurping 
radio and television ahead of the presidential campaign. 
  Shushkevich's campaign managers issued a statement saying 
"the government's propaganda machine for Kebich's nomination was 
switched on long before the election itself." They said "any 
provision of air time to Kebich's rivals carried the risk of a 
journalist's dismissal" adding that perpetual appearance on 
radio and television by Kebich and his team was unfair. 
  Campaign managers of two other candidates have also accused 
the Prime Minister of using central and local government staff 
in his presidential campaign. 
  In the meantime, President of the National Bank Stanislav 
Bogdankevich told Interfax that all of the heads of NBB branches 
had been warned against financing any of the presidential 
candidates. In this connection, the Bank will also tighten 
control over commercial bank operations, he said. 
  IF Note: Representatives of nine pro-democracy groups and 
movements set up a public supervisory commission to make sure 
that the forthcoming election is free and fair. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

