<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Aliyev Visit to Belgium </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Aliyev Visit to Belgium </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Signs Partnership for Peace </H4>

<F P=102> LD0405135894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1301 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Mineyev] </F>
  [Text] Brussels, 4 May -- Today Azerbaijan became the 15th 
country to join the "Partnership for Peace" program proposed by 
NATO countries and states of Eastern Europe and the former 
Soviet Union. Geydar Aliyev, president of Azerbaijan, signed the 
program's outline document at the NATO Brussels headquarters 
today. 
  Speaking at the signing ceremony, Aliyev stressed that his 
country adheres to the principles of democracy and free 
enterprise. Its foreign policy proceeds from the principle of 
interdependence of the present-day world and is based on the 
principles of respect for national independence, sovereignty, 
territorial integrity, and nonviolation of borders. 
  At the same time, Aliyev noted, Azerbaijan is experiencing a 
grave economic crisis caused by a collapse of ties with the 
former Soviet republics and the transition to a new economic 
system. The crisis is being aggravated by the armed conflict 
with Armenia. Aliyev stated there is no military solution to the 
conflict and favors stepping up the efforts of international 
organizations, first of all the UNO and the CSCE Minsk group, 
aimed to attain a settlement at the negotiation table. The 
conditions put forward by his country for these talks consist of 
an immediate cease-fire and the withdrawal of Armenian troops 
from Azerbaijan's occupied territories. The talks should ensure 
Azerbaijan's territorial integrity. It is only after this that 
Baku is prepared to examine the issue of a status of autonomy 
for Nagornyy Karabakh. 
  In signing the document on partnership, Azerbaijan, 
according 
to Aliyev, visualizes for itself two main goals for the 
development of cooperation with NATO: the country's integration 
into Western democracy and its quest for additional ways to 
stabilize the situation in the Caucasus and to end the war 
between Azerbaijan and Armenia. 
  Sergio Balanzino, the NATO deputy secretary general who 
chaired today's session of the NATO Council, noted that regional 
conflicts today are a serious threat to stability and security 
in the zone of Europe and the Atlantic. Within the framework of 
the Council for North Atlantic Cooperation, which includes both 
Azerbaijan and Armenia, the countries of the alliance are making 
efforts to mediate with the purpose of a peaceful settlement to 
the conflict. He welcomed the measures taken in this direction 
by the Minsk CSCE group, stressing that only a solution of this 
kind can bring peace back to the region. Participation in the 
"Partnership for Peace" program will develop in accordance with 
the the tempo and content Azerbaijan itself determines, 
Balanzino noted, expressing the hope that this cooperation would 
contribute to stability and security in Transcaucasia and 
throughout the Euro-Atlantic zone. 
  Also today Geydar Aliyev met the Belgian Prime Minister 
Jean-Luc Dehaene. He invited the head of the Belgian Government 
to visit Azerbaijan and expressed confidence that a treaty of 
friendship and cooperation between the two countries would be 
signed during his visit to Baku. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61260 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov087_r_94005" </HT>


