<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev, Christopher Urge Geneva Meeting on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev, Christopher Urge Geneva Meeting on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405182294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1721 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By unidentified ITAR-TASS special correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Cairo, 4 May -- Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev and U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher expressed 
serious concern over the unstable situation that still pertains 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina and which contains the threat of a 
flare-up of new dangerous hot-beds of conflict. During a 
meeting that took place today in the Egyptian capital, the heads 
of the foreign policy departments of the two countries called on 
the warring sides immediately and totally to implement a 
withdrawal of forces from the established zones around Gorazde 
and to undertake immediate steps to reduce tension and to 
prevent offensive military actions in the region of Brcko. 
  Kozyrev and Christopher also called for the signing, as soon 
as possible, of an agreement on a total cessation of hostilities 
over the whole territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina that would 
envisage the disengagement of military formations, the 
withdrawal of heavy weapons, and the stationing of UN forces 
between them. They called for the immediate renewal of talks 
without preconditions in order to work out a comprehensive 
settlement in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Russia's foreign minister and the U.S. secretary of state 
are 
convinced of the necessity for providing a powerful political 
impulse to the process of finding a Bosnian settlement. They 
call for the holding of a meeting at ministerial level with the 
participation of the member countries of the contact group. 
Such a meeting could take place in Geneva on 13 May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61275 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov087_a_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Future Bosnia Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More on Future Bosnia Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405192094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1819 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow and Washington for the first time showed 
complete agreement on the necessity for an urgent international 
meeting on a settlement in Bosnia. This was announced by 
Kozyrev's Advisor Galina Sidorova when commenting on the meeting 
between Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and U.S. 
secretary of State Warren Christopher in Cairo today. 
  Sidorova said that they had discussed a possible meeting 
between the foreign ministers of the states involved in the 
settlement of the Bosnian crisis which might take place in 
Geneva in the near future. Sidorova said the terms were still 
being worked upon. For instance, Russia, the USA, three EU 
members -- France, Germany and Great Britain and international 
mediators Torvald Stoltenberg and Lord Owen are expected to 
participate. The final date will be defined during 
consultations between the future participants in the meeting. 
  This meeting will open the way for a summit on a settlement 
in Bosnia with the same countries participating. Kozyrev and 
Christopher were deeply concerned over the situation around the 
Bosnian city of Brcko. The situation in Brcko calls for an 
agreement in order to put an end to all military actions on 
Bosnian territory, Sidorova said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

