<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meeting Expected in `Next Few Days' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meeting Expected in `Next Few Days' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505061794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0606 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505061794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov and </F>
ITAR- TASS correspondent Georgiy Shelenkov] 
  [Text] Cairo May 5 TASS -- For the first time Russia and 
the United States are unanimous in calling for a quadrilateral 
ministerial conference on the settlement of the Bosnian 
conflict. The conference will bring together representatives of 
the Russian Federation, the United States, the European Union 
and the United Nations to work out a single plan for the 
settlement. 
  It can be surmised that in addition to the two great powers, 
France, Germany and Britain, who are playing a prominent role in 
unblocking the situation, are likely to take part in the talks. 
The meeting will take place in Geneva "literally in the next 
few days", according to a ranking official of the Russian 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs. 
  The Geneva ministerial forum, according to the official, can 
become a prologue to a summit, involving all interested 
countries, as proposed by Moscow. The idea of a multilateral 
conference is dictated by an understanding that the guarantees 
of any one party cannot lead to the settlement of the conflict 
but can only further exacerbate the problem. 
  The Russian official stressed that the prompt setting in 
motion of a mechanism of multilateral negotiations is 
necessitated by the volatile situation in the area of Brcko. 
Bitter experience has made clear to every one where such 
situations might lead. To achieve a universal end to combat 
activities is now a high priority task, the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

