<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Republics, Regions Threatened With Gas Cutoff </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Republics, Regions Threatened With Gas Cutoff </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405193594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1819 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's natural gas monopoly Gazprom has warned 
several republics and regions of the Russian Federation that it 
would cut off gas supplies to their industrial enterprises due 
to their debts. 
  In telegrams sent to the republics of Karachay-Circassia, 
Ingushetia, Kabardino-Balkaria, North Ossetia, Bashkiria and 
Daghestan, to Perm, Novosibirsk, Astrakhan, Kemerovo, Rostov and 
Voronezh Regions, and to Stavropol Territory, Gazprom says it 
will suspend its gas deliveries to them between May 4 and 9 and 
demands that they present schedules for the payment of their 
arrears, totaling about three billion rubles, a sum which, 
according to Gazprom sources, is much higher than the overall 
debt for Russian gas of other former Soviet republics, including 
Ukraine, Belarus and Moldova. 
  The sources told the Oil Information Agency that Moldova had 
still not presented its own schedule for the repayment of a debt 
which had reached 131 billion rubles by April 1. As of April 
15, Gazprom slashed its supplies to Moldova by one-third. The 
sources said that this year the republic had transferred "not a 
single ruble" to Gazprom's bank account, having paid part of its 
arrears with food exports. The Russian-Moldovan talks on the 
debt problem, originally scheduled for the end of April, have 
been postponed until this Friday, the sources said. 
  In an agreement signed by the two countries' governments 
late 
last year, Moldova pledged to send to Russia 145 million 
dollars' worth of food and consumer goods as payment for part of 
the 3.5 billion cubic meters of gas the republic is due to 
receive from Gazprom this year. 
  Russia today charges Moldova 80 dollars for 1,000 cubic 
meters of gas. Moldova, in turn, charges Russia 1.5 dollars per 
100 kilometers for every 1,000 cubic meters of gas pipelined 
through Moldovan territory to Romania. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

