<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Claims `No Military Aims' in Estonia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Claims `No Military Aims' in Estonia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505095794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0925 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505095794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Maloveriyan] </F>
  [Text] Tallinn May 5 TASS -- Russia and Estonia are toiling 
over a draft agreement on the withdrawal of Russian troops from 
that Baltic republic. According to the leader of the Estonian 
delegation Vaino Reinart, Estonia is ready to sign the agreement 
and "the only obstacle to the signing is Russia's desire to link 
the problem to the provision of social guarantees to the Russian 
Army pensioners residing in the republic". 
  The Russian delegation leader Vasili Svirin met Estonian 
President Lennart Meri on the eve of the today's round of 
negotiations. According to him, the results of their 
conversation provide grounds for the hope that the parties to 
the drawn-out "divorce procedure" between Russia and Estonia 
will be able to muster enough strength and desire to get down to 
the search for compromise solutions. 
  "Russia pursues no military aims or interests in Estonia," 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin declared in the Kremlin on 
Wednesday. He stressed that "Russia intends to withdraw all 
troops from Estonia, but we want this to be done on a legal 
basis, as is being done in relations between Russia and 
Lithuania, Russia and Latvia". If Estonia manifests good-will, 
we for our part will respond with full accord", Yeltsin said. 
  Negotiations behind closed doors will last for two days. 
After the end of this, the nineteenth round of negotiations, 
the heads of the delegations are expected to hold press 
conferences on the results of negotiations. 

</TEXT>

