<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Minister Offers Assistance in Closing Chernobyl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    French Minister Offers Assistance in Closing Chernobyl </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405124594 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 1115 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Kiev, 4 May -- "The election of a new parliament 
marked the end of a period of political indecision in Ukraine," 
said Alain Lamassoure, the French minister delegate for European 
affairs, at a news conference concluding an official visit to 
Ukraine by a French delegation. France is interested in 
expanding cooperation with the independent Ukrainian state, he 
said. To assist this, agreements have been signed in the course 
of the visit on the encouragement and protection of investments, 
on air transport, on cultural exchanges, and on youth and sport 
cooperation and exchanges. [passage omitted] During their visit 
to Ukraine, the French delegation discussed issues concerning 
energy resources and nuclear power engineering. France has 
proposed, Mr. Lamassoure noted, that issues regarding nuclear 
power engineering in Ukraine be discussed at the forthcoming G-7 
summit in Naples. 
  France is offering Ukraine help in preparing a project to 
shut down all generating sets at the Chernobyl nuclear electric 
power station and complete the construction of three generating 
sets at other nuclear electric power stations to compensate for 
power losses caused by the closure. "We do realize, however, 
that the cost of these projects is very high and that only 
international financial support will enable Ukraine to carry 
them out," Mr. Lamassoure stressed. France is ready to promise 
such support to Ukraine, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

