Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Thanks France for Help </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Thanks France for Help </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405150494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1429 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov and Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] At the meeting in Kiev with the Minister for 
European Affairs, Alain Lamassoure, President Kravchuk expressed 
gratitude to France for help it provides to Ukraine in scrapping 
nuclear weapons and providing safety for nuclear power stations. 
He said that the country's leadership appreciates a change in 
the relationships between the West and Ukraine after the 
three-partite agreement on nuclear weapons was signed in Moscow. 
  France's representatives are part of the G-7 delegation 
currently in Ukraine, which arrived in the Republic to study the 
situation at Ukrainian nuclear power stations. Deputy Prime 
Minister Valeriy Shmarov told reporters that Ukrainian leaders 
will sign no documents on the results of the visit with G-7 
inspectors. 
  INTERFAX note: The delegation includes senior officials of 
the G-7 nuclear energy ministries, the nuclear security fund of 
the European Bank for the Reconstruction and Development, the 
U.S. Department of State. The delegation intends to prepare 
materials for the G-7 summit in Naples, which explain the need 
of the economic aid to Ukraine. 
  Shmarov said that at their meeting members of the delegation 
expressed preparedness to provide a financial aid to Ukraine in 
the development of the nuclear energy and for higher level of 
safety at the Ukrainian nuclear power stations. This aid will 
be given if Ukraine refuses to commission the second block of 
the Chernobyl nuclear power station and agrees to the gradual 
closure of the first and third operating blocks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

