Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Says $3 Billion Needed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegation Says $3 Billion Needed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405180694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1729 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405180694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and Mikhail </F>
Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev May 4 TASS -- G-7 countries understand 
Ukraine's concerns about the Chernobyl nuclear power plant, but 
have not made any commitments to extend much needed financial 
support, a Ukrainian high-ranking official said. 
  In an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS on Wednesday, 
Mikhail Umanets, chairman of the Ukrainian State Committee for 
Nuclear Power Engineering, said that Ukraine is ready to shut 
down the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in return for financial 
assistance. 
  A Ukrainian governmental delegation met with a group of G-7 
officials in Kiev today to discuss the issue. The Ukrainian 
side said it needs over 3 billion U.S. dollars to go ahead with 
the plan of closure. 
  However, there has been no response from G-7 officials yet, 
Umanets said. He said that the matter has been handed over to a 
special working group set up today. 
  Detailed reports on the problem will be submitted to the 
upcoming G-7 summit meeting in Naples. Umanets did not rule out 
the possibility that "the sides will reach a consensus" in 
Naples. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

