<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Environment Minister on Closing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Environment Minister on Closing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405194794 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1800 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yuriy Kostenko, Ukraine's environmental protection 
minister, on 4 May met representatives of a G-7 mission, which 
is on a visit to Ukraine. The visitors took interest in the 
problem of closing down the Chernobyl nuclear power plant as 
soon as possible and other issues relating to the use of 
radioactive materials in Ukraine. By closing down the Chernobyl 
AES, in the view of the mission's representatives, Ukraine would 
make a considerable contribution to guaranteeing the ecological 
safety of Europe. 
  Yuriy Kostenko said MinPryrody [Environmental Protection 
Ministry] was steadily insistent on the plant's closure. 
Because of Ukraine's complex economic situation, however, a 
speedy settlement to the issue, in the minister's view, is only 
possible given adequate financial and technological assistance 
from the G-7 countries. 
  As for the future of radioactive waste and used nuclear 
fuel, 
Yuriy Kostenko said that the only possible way for Ukraine now 
was to store them in makeshift depots until a national nuclear 
waste repository would be built. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61302 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov087_e_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Urges Shutdown </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Urges Shutdown </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405192994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1819 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The continuing use of the Chernobyl nuclear power 
station is a permanent source of danger not only for Ukraine, 
but also for other countries of the world, head of the G-7 
working group for nuclear security, Antonio Puri Purini said in 
Kiev Wednesday [4 May]. He is the head of a G-7 mission in 
Ukraine probing into the republic's nuclear security. 
  At his meeting with the mission's officials, Ukrainian 
Environmental Protection Minister Yuriy Kostenko drew everyone's 
attention to the fact that his ministry was the only body which 
insisted on immediate shut down of the station. 
  In Kostenko's opinion, measures taken to ensure the 
station's 
safety are not a guarantee that the surrounding territory would 
not be contaminated in case of an accident. 
  Kostenko pointed out that under the difficult economic 
situation faced currently by Ukraine a prompt solution of the 
Chernobyl issue was possible only provided "adequate" financial 
and technical assistance by G-7 countries. The minister pointed 
out that the situation was further complicated by nuclear 
disarmament underway in Ukraine, "which is an expensive and 
laborious process." 
  Commenting on dumping nuclear waste and exhausted fuel, 
Kostenko said the only acceptable variant for Ukraine would be 
storing such waste in temporary facilities until a stationary 
storage is constructed. 
  As INTERFAX-Ukraine learned, the deputies' group preparing 
the first session of the newly elected republican parliament had 
failed to include the commission for Chernobyl issues in the 
panel of commissions to be approved by the new parliament's 
first session. 
  The Ukrainian Party of Justice and the Chernobyl Union held 
a 
news conference in Kiev Wednesday calling on the deputies not to 
abolish the commission. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

