<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intergovernmental Economic Talks With U.S. Under Way </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intergovernmental Economic Talks With U.S. Under Way </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405140394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1304 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Official Ukrainian-American negotiations on economic 
cooperation are underway in Kiev. Ukraine's Economics Minister 
Roman Shpek and special adviser of the U.S. President Nicholas 
Burns head the delegations. 
  In the course of these talks the parties are discussing 
problems related to rendering assistance to Ukraine in the 
sphere of privatization, trade, investments, and allocation of 
funds to procure medicines and food products. 
  The American party has again reaffirmed its readiness to 
support concrete and intensive reforms in the economy and to 
push for assistance to Ukraine from the G-7, International 
Monetary Fund, World Bank, and European Bank for Reconstruction 
and Development. 
  According to Roman Shpek, "speeding up of the opportunity to 
receive financial, technical, and credit assistance for 
Ukrainian economic subjects of all forms of ownership" is one of 
the major tasks of these negotiations. 
  In the course of the meetings the parties exchanged their 
opinions regarding the work of the American-Ukrainian Fund in 
support of private enterprises. The U.S. Government has already 
allocated $150 million for the three-year program of this fund. 

</TEXT>

