<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Round of Talks With Russia Begins in Tallinn </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Round of Talks With Russia Begins in Tallinn </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505092894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0804 
GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0505092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Maloveryan] </F>
  [Text] Tallinn, 5 May (ITAR-TASS) -- A regular round of 
Russian-Estonian talks started here today. It is devoted to 
work on a treaty on the withdrawal of Russian troops from 
Estonia. 
  According to Vaino Reinart, head of the Estonian delegation, 
Estonia is ready to sign this act and Russia's desire to link 
this problem with the provision of social guarantees to the 
Russian military pensioners residing in the republic is the only 
stumbling block. 
  On the eve of the round Vasiliy Svirin, head of the Russian 
delegation, met with Estonian President Lennart Meri. The 
results of the conversation, he believes, give cause for hope 
that in a prolonged Russian-Estonian "divorce suit dialogue" the 
parties can find strength and willingness to engage in a search 
for a compromise to settle the problem. 
  The talks are being held behind closed doors and will last 
for two days. It is planned that a news conference will be 
given by the heads of delegations on the results of the talks. 

</TEXT>

