<H3> <TI>   Council of Europe Delegation Visits Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council of Europe Delegation Visits Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0505090494 Tallinn BNS in English 1515 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0505090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, May 04, BNS -- A Council of Europe 
Parliamentary Assembly subcommittee delegation had meetings in 
Tallinn today with a deputy speaker of the Estonian parliament, 
members of the parliament's social affairs commission, Social 
Affairs Ministry officials. 
  The delegation of the subcommittee for social rights under 
the Social, Health and Family Affairs Committee of the 
Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe includes 
representatives from the Netherlands, Germany, Britain, France, 
Italy and Ireland. 
  Members of the Estonian parliament's social affairs 
commission, Social Security Department and Social Affairs 
Ministry officials at their meeting with the delegation spoke 
about the country's steps in working out a new pensions system 
to take into account also the wage level of each employee. 
  The first step in the creation of the new system is a 
national employers registry, work on which was finished Tuesday 
[3 May], said Georg Mannik, the head of the Social Security 
Department. 
  A transition to the new system is planned for the next year, 
he said. 
  Toomas Vilosius, adviser at the Social Affairs Ministry, 
spoke about the Estonian health insurance system. 
  Political situation in Estonia and the legislative activity 
were the main topics discussed at a meeting of the delegation 
with Estonian parliament's Deputy Speaker Tunne Kelam earlier 
today. Kelam spoke about Estonia's plans for further integration 
with Europe. The delegation members asked questions about 
various aspects of the legislation, the country's economic 
development and the problem of the retired Russian military, the 
parliament press office reports. 
  A separate meeting with the chair of the parliamentary 
social 
affairs commission, Siiri Oviir, and visits to social welfare 
sector establishments in Tallinn were scheduled for the 
afternoon. 
  The delegation will visit Narva for meetings with 
representatives of the northeastern city's Estonian and Russian 
communities, as well as visits to social security institutions 
Thursday. 

</TEXT>

