<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Businessmen To Sign Accord Agreement in Kremlin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Businessmen To Sign Accord Agreement in Kremlin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505061294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0605 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505061294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 5 TASS -- A second stage of signing an 
agreement on civic accord will be held in the Kremlin today. 
The document will be signed by representatives of industrial, 
banking and entrepreneurial associations, president's chief of 
staff Sergey Filatov told ITAR-TASS that over 200 public 
organisations declared that they were ready to sign the 
agreement. [sentence as recevied] 
  The agreement provides for main guarantees of stability in 
society, making amendments to the constitution by means of 
conciliatory procedures, pledges not to stage political 
campaigns for the purpose of holding early elections and a ban 
on the use of force methods in the settlement of conflicts. 
  The first stage of signing the civic accord pact was held on 
April 28, when the document was signed by leaders of executive 
and legislative branches of power, subjects of the federation, 
representatives of political, public and religious organisations. 
  According to Filatov, the agreement on civic accord has 
"positively affected the general climate in society and clearly 
showed a strong will of the Russian people to attain peace and 
calm." Filatov is convinced that the agreement on civic accord 
will help avoid political turmoils and create normal conditions 
for carrying out economic reforms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

