<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agrarians To Decide on Accord Treaty Signing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agrarians To Decide on Accord Treaty Signing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405162694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1503 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Leaders of the Agrarian Party and its parliamentary 
faction, the Agrarian Union and the Agricultural Trade Union 
Central Committee will meet in Moscow on May 10 in order to 
examine and to weigh up once again the agreement on agricultural 
policy guidelines for the next two years. The agreement has 
recently been signed with the Russian government. Afterwards, 
the Agrarians will make their final decision whether or not to 
sign the treaty on civil accord. This was announced by Deputy 
Chairman of the Agrarian Union, Gennadiy Kulik. The union 
includes Russia's biggest agricultural enterprises. 
  Kulik suggested that this meeting was needed since none of 
the signatories had as yet seen the final text of the document. 
That is why the Agrarian Party, the Agrarian Union and the 
Agricultural Trade Union wanted to make sure if the government 
had accepted all their demands. 
  In particular, the Agrarians insisted that the government 
included into the treaty a number of obligations in order to 
prevent forceful pressure on farmers when choosing forms of 
property, to ensure Russia's independence in food supply and to 
support the agricultural regions with 10 or 15 percent of the 
budget expenses. Several other conditions have also been put 
forward. 
  The agreement was signed on April 30 on the day after the 
ceremony of signing of the treaty on civil accord in the 
Kremlin. The Agrarian leaders did not take part in the ceremony. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

