<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Declares Russia Major Partner, Ally </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akayev Declares Russia Major Partner, Ally </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405140194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1304 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia is Kyrgyzstan's major partner and its 
strategic ally, Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev declared during 
his meeting with Chairman of Russia's Federation Council 
Vladimir Shumeyko on Wednesday [4 May] in Bishkek. 
  In the course of their conversation Akayev pointed out that 
Kyrgyzstan and Russia maintain traditional friendly and 
partnership relations. However, in his opinion, there are 
several problems in the republic related to migration of the 
Russian-speaking population. 
  Akayev underlined, that Kyrgyzstan does its utmost to solve 
this problem. In his words, it needs Russia's assistance. He 
indicated that the Slavic University formed in Bishkek in which 
the Republic's Russian-speaking population can receive an 
education represents "one of the examples of the 
Russian-speaking population's strengthening." 
  As Akayev said, it is necessary to create other institutes 
and organizations so as to lower the level of Russian migration 
from Kyrgyzstan. He also pointed out that in the near term the 
Republic's government would adopt a state program in order to 
keep its Russian-speaking population from leaving. 
  Shumeyko underlined that Russia is ready to render economic 
assistance to Kyrgyzstan, in particular, "to support the 
Republic's regions, which have suffered from natural disasters." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

