<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia, U.S. Come To Rescue in Mideast Peace Signing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia, U.S. Come To Rescue in Mideast Peace Signing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405191194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1824 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov and </F>
ITAR-TASS correspondent Georgiy Shelenkov] 
  [Text] Cairo, 4 May -- The Russian-U.S. cosponsorship of 
the search for a Middle East settlement has passed a stern test. 
The heads of the two countries' diplomatic departments spent 
two days in the Egyptian capital making strenuous mediating 
efforts to bring to a successful finale the talks between the 
Palestine Liberation Organization and Israel, which were crowned 
today by the conclusion of an historic "peace protocol." Even 
during the actual signing ceremony, the intermediaries had to 
come urgently to the assistance of the sides. 
  Several details of the dramatic episode, which almost 
obliterated the many months of the "peace marathon," have become 
known to ITAR-TASS correspondents from informed sources. As he 
appended his signature to the agreement, Yasir 'Arafat demanded 
from the United States and Russia additional security guarantees 
for the territories now being freed. During an enforced break 
in the signing procedure, the cosponsors gave him the relevant 
assurances, which insured the Palestinian leader's agreement to 
sign the document. Experts from the two great powers started 
consultations on the matter today, and the guarantees are 
expected to be countersigned tomorrow by the Russian and U.S. 
heads of diplomacy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61342 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov087_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Upbeat on PLO-Israeli Peace Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Upbeat on PLO-Israeli Peace Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405143994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1359 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Rafael Bikbayev] </F>
  [Text] Cairo May 4 TASS -- Russia is interested in 
stability in the Middle East which is located in geographical 
proximity to its borders, Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev said in Cairo on Wednesday. 
  Kozyrev attended the ceremony of signing a peace accord 
between Israel and the PLO to implement limited Palestinian 
self-rule. 
  "It is the proof of our closeness that it takes four hours 
to 
fly from Moscow to the Middle East and twice as much to the 
Russian borders," he said. 
  "I am convinced that PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli 
Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin are well aware of Russia's 
adherence to regional settlement as one of the co-sponsors of 
the peace process," Kozyrev continued. 
  He pointed up three key aspects in the Middle East peace 
process. The first one is Palestinian autonomy in the Gaza Strip 
and the town of Jericho. The second one is peaceful 
co-existence and mutual respect between Israel and Palestinians 
and "probably even cooperation between them in the future." And 
lastly, comprehensive settlement in the region. 
  "We hope that it will be reached in the not so distant 
future 
and we will witness the signing of an agreement on not only the 
Gaza Strip and the town of Jericho, but also other territories," 
the Russian foreign minister added. 
  Kozyrev praised the "outstanding role" of Egyptian President 
Husni Mubarak in furthering the peace process in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

