Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Urges Pressure on Bosnian Warring Factions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Urges Pressure on Bosnian Warring Factions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405140494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1304 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There is dangerous brinkmanship in Bosnia today. In 
this situation, the key world community members should take 
energetic steps and exert pressure to prevent war and restore 
peace there, the Russian President's Special Envoy Vitaliy 
Churkin, a deputy foreign minister, declared in an interview 
with Interfax on Wednesday. 
  In his words, pressure should be applied to both sides, the 
Bosnian Serbs and the Bosnian Moslems. "There is a war of 
nerves going on at Brcko, a confrontation that, in principle, 
could result in a military clash. That is why energetic actions 
and pressure are essential. What this really means is that the 
sides should sign an agreement that would end hostilities, 
disengage the troops, and would enable the UN to deploy its 
protection force in former Yugoslavia between the two hostile 
factions," Churkin said. 
  In his words, Russia's proposal to convene a conference on 
Bosnia with Russia's foreign minister, US Secretary of State, EC 
and UN representatives to take part aims at putting pressure on 
the belligerents. 
  Asked when and where such a gathering could take place, 
Churkin replied, "That may be known shortly. The issue has been 
discussed by the Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and his 
American counterpart Warren Christopher upon their arrival in 
Cairo to attend a ceremony for signing Israeli-Palestinian 
accords on Gaza and Jericho." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

