<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Russia International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on `New Ideas' for Bosnian Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev on `New Ideas' for Bosnian Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604151694 Moscow RIA in English 1333 GMT 26 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2604151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 26, RIA -- "We are carrying with us 
new ideas as to how feed and intensify the political direction 
of Bosnian settlement," Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said in 
an exclusive interview before his flight to Geneva to discuss 
Yugoslav problems with US Secretary of State Warren Christopher. 
  "The military tendency is now looming quite distinctly due 
to 
irresponsible activities of Serbian commandos, but, let us hope, 
they won't go so far as to realise their plans," said Kozyrev. 
  In his words, the Security Council is busy reviewing all the 
apsects of likely military measures on the part of NATO. "We 
have succeeded in preventing nato from having a free hand in any 
such action, it is the Security Council which is now to follow 
it very intently". Kozyrev expressed the hope that the Serbs 
will continue performing their obligations before the UN and, 
correspondingly, the UN will not be confronted with the need to 
decide on NATO strikes. "But all will depend on the Bosnian 
Serbs' conduct," stressed Kozyrev, noting that, despite the 
possibility of military measures, the right decision should be 
sought on the political plane. 
  The minister reported that he was in touch with Serbian 
President Slobodan Milosevic and received from him today an 
answer to his message, in which Milosevic expresses the desire 
to sustain constructive cooperation with Russia, he showed 
understanding of the Russian position. 
  In the words of Kozyrev, he was going in the next two-three 
days to meet French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and, perhaps, 
foreign ministers of a number of other Western states to discuss 
the same problems. "The next two-three days will see intensive 
diplomatic arrangements, which, as I think, should open a way 
toward the closing stage--a summit for rounding off all this 
tragic episode," said Kozyrev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61350 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov088__a94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-088-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Russia International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Comments on Bosnian Peace Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Comments on Bosnian Peace Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2704154694 Moscow RIA in English 1509 GMT 27 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2704154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 27, RIA. There is "the will and the 
opportunity" for a realistic partnership aiming to attain 
political settlement in Bosnia. Now is the time for joint 
action, said Russia's Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev at a press 
conference upon the completion of his talks with Alain Juppe, 
foreign minister of France, who arrived in Geneva today. 
  Said Kozyrev in reply to a RIA question: "The main 
conclusion 
after the talks is that there is the need to unite efforts for a 
political settlement in Bosnia in order to preclude a new wave 
of violence in the region. My partners and I are optimistic: we 
believe there is a realistic opportunity to attain settlement. 
We would like to hold - in the near future - a working meet of 
foreign ministers to prepare a summit meeting with the 
participation of the UN." 
  On the possibility of new NATO strikes in the former 
Yugoslavia, the minister said that everything depended on 
specific circumstances. If there are new barbaric shellings of 
civilian targets, everything will depend on a specific 
situation. "The main thing is that we have made NATO's military 
plans not so much the plans of that organization, but the plans 
of the UN Security Council to be applied in the worst 
situation," Kozyrev noted. The procedure for the 
decision-making on the issue is well known: all operations 
should be seen as being within the framework of the UN 
Peace-keeping effort. 
  M. Juppe said that he accords "exceedingly great importance" 
to the talks with the Russian minister. He called them rather 
productive and said that they would continue soon. He plans to 
visit Moscow on May 19. 
  France has always maintained close contact with Russia on 
the 
issue of the Bosnian settlement, Juppe said. Today's talks are 
seen as very important in the light of the situation there. 
  Today, Andrey Kozyrev had a telephone conversation with UN 
Secretary General's Envoy Yakusi Akashi. The two officials 
noted the normalisation of the situation around Gorazde, which 
lays the ground for the processes of a peaceful settlement in 
Bosnia and Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

