<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Russia International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin To Cease Active Participation in Bosnia Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin To Cease Active Participation in Bosnia Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2704195594 Moscow RIA in English 1800 GMT 27 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2704195594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 27, RIA -- Vitaliy Churkin, special 
representative of the Russian president in former Yugoslavia, 
will no longer "actively participate" in Bosnian settlement. 
This high-ranking Russian diplomat told newsmen today that his 
place in the contact group established to step up UN peacemaking 
efforts in Bosnia will be occupied by Aleksey Nikiforov who has 
"direct experience" of work in former Yugoslavia. The new 
contact group, which comprises Russian, American, French, 
German, and british officials, heads for Sarajevo April 28. 
"I'll maintain links with it and, probably take part in its work 
from time to time" said Mr. Churkin. But he is going to focus 
his efforts on Russia's possible affiliation to NATO's 
partnership in the name of peace program. 
  Western diplomats watching developments in former Yugoslavia 
do not rule out that Mr. Churkin's departure at such a 
responsible moment may be connected with his recent harsh 
statements regarding the Bosnian Serbians who angered them very 
much. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

