<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Russia International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow To Tighten Control Over Foreign Fishing Boats </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow To Tighten Control Over Foreign Fishing Boats </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004134794 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2004134794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yoichi Nishimura] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Apr -- Russia has decided to tighten law 
enforcement against poaching boats in the Sea of Okhotsk and 
other waters off the Far East, including the northern 
territories [Kuril Islands], starting on 20 April. 
  The crackdown is code named the "Fishing Season '94" 
operation, and it involves mobilization of the Border Patrol, 
local government authorities in the Far East, Russian Navy's 
Pacific Fleet, and even reconnaissance satellites. Several 
Japanese fishing boats have recently been captured in waters off 
the northern territories, and the Russian crackdown is obviously 
targeting these Japanese fishermen. 
  On 19 April, Border Patrol Commander Nikolayev stated as 
follows in Kamchatka: "As an economic major power, Russia has 
to protect its own economic interests. Our neighbors should not 
forget about it. Russia intends to establish `civilized' border 
lines -- this means the border exists to secure national 
interests." 
  The crackdown on poachers will be continued until October. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

