<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission Vows To Protect Russians in Former USSR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission Vows To Protect Russians in Former USSR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604104394 Moscow RIA in English 1004 GMT 26 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2604104394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 26, RIA -- The Russian Federation will 
pursue a policy of protecting and supporting Russians on the 
territory of the former USSR by carrying out a package of state 
programmes, which stipulate political, diplomatic, information, 
economic, social and cultural measures. This was stressed at a 
conference in Moscow, organised by the Commission on 
Citizenship, attached to the president, and the Russian Foreign 
Ministry. 
  The report of the committee chairman Abdullah Mikitayev says 
that special attention will be paid to the situation of ethnic 
Russians in Latvia and Estonia, many of whom have been denied 
citizenship. He said that he advocates the granting of the 
Russian citizenship to them, if they want it, and stressed that 
the settlement of the problem of ethnic Russians in ex-soviet 
states as soon as possible meets the interests of both Russia 
and newly-independent states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61363 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov088__a94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-088-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin, Communications Union Head Discuss Post </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin, Communications Union Head Discuss Post </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904173794 Moscow RIA in English 1510 GMT 29 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2904173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 29, RIA -- At the moment the Russian 
state-operated postal service finds itself on the brink of 
bankruptcy, says a press release issued by the State Duma of the 
Russian Federation. 
  Despite 15.9 billion roubles in subsidies received from the 
budget in 1993, the postal Workers paid 20 billion roubles in 
taxes. 
  The 1994 federal budget allocates no funds at all for the 
development and social needs of the postal services. 
  These facts were cited by Anatoliy Nazeykin, the chairman of 
the Communication Workers' Union, at a meeting with State Duma 
Chairman Ivan Rybkin on April 29. 
  Since the service is not profitable, post offices are 
closing 
down in many regions, with postal workers being dismissed. 
  Such a situation, in the view of the union leaders, may 
affect the interests of the population, disrupting the regular 
delivery of pensions and benefits and periodicals. 
  Rybkin backed the communication workers' request that the 
house should consider exempting the state-run postal services 
subsidised from the budget from value added tax and a special 
tax on services rendered to the population, as well as from 
taxes on press distribution and acceptance of international mail. 
  He also promised to speed up the examination and adoption of 
federal laws on communications and on federal postal services. 

</TEXT>

