<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijan Refuses To Sign Accord on Nagorno-Karabakh </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Azerbaijan Refuses To Sign Accord on Nagorno-Karabakh </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505154994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1521 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Maynayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek May 5 TASS -- Negotiations between lawmakers 
from Azerbaijan, Armenia, Kyrgyzstan, Russia and representatives 
of Nagorno-Karabakh have gave no result, because the Azerbaijani 
party refused to sign the final protocol on Thursday. [sentence 
as received] 
  "We worked day and night to put together the two-page 
document, but failed to reach an agreement," Vladimir Shumeyko, 
chairman of the Federation Council (Russian parliament's upper 
house), who led the Russian delegation at the talks, told 
ITAR-TASS despondingly as he walked out into a corridor inside 
the Bishkek governmental palace, where the talks were held. 
  The participants in the talks refused to talk with the 
journalists. 
  Next time, they will tackle the Nagorno-Karabakh issues in 
the St. Petersburg-based headquarters of the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly. 
  They are to leave Bishkek for their home countries on 
Thursday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61379 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov088cc_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Refusal To Sign Cease-Fire Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Refusal To Sign Cease-Fire Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505145994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1320 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The chief Azerbaijani negotiator on Thursday refused 
to sign in Bishkek, Kyrgyzstan, a protocol appealing to the 
parties in the conflict over Azerbaijan's disputed enclave of 
Nagorno-Karabakh to stop fire. 
  The protocol, based on an accord signed by the Armenian, 
Azerbaijani and Russian defense ministers in Moscow on March 18, 
has been discussed by parliamentary representatives from 
Armenia, Azerbaijan and Nagorno-Karabakh at a two-day meeting in 
Bishkek mediated by a mission of the Interparliamentary Assembly 
of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS). The document, 
calling for ceasefire as of midnight on May 8, has been signed 
by all other negotiators, Armenian Parliamentary Chairman Babken 
Ararktsian, Nagorno-Karabakh Parliamentary Chairman Karen 
Baburian, and the mediators, Vladimir Shumeyko, chairman of the 
Interparliamentary Assembly and head of the upper house of the 
Russian parliament, Medetkan Medetkulov, head of Kyrgyzstan's 
parliament and leader of the Interparliamentary Assembly peace 
group for Nagorno-Karabakh, and Vladimir Kazimirov, special 
envoy of the Russian president. 
  The protocol also urged the warring sides to sign as early 
as 
possible an agreement to rule out any more hostilities and 
provide a mechanism to withdraw troops from occupied 
territories, restore communications, enable refugees to return 
home and provide a basis for further talks. 
  Azerbaijan's head negotiator, Deputy Parliamentary Chairman 
Afiyaddin Dzhalilov, told a news briefing following the talks 
that his country disagreed with some points in the protocol, 
namely the fact that it does not mention Armenia's occupation of 
Azerbaijani lands and the proposal to deploy a CIS peacekeeping 
force in the conflict zone. He also said Azerbaijan's proposal 
that a representative of Nagorno-Karabakh's Azeri community be 
added to the signatories had been rejected. "The Azerbaijani 
side is not pursuing any political ambitions but is trying to 
make proposals reflecting the real situation in the conflict 
zone," he said. 
  Shumeyko said at the briefing that it would be impossible to 
settle the conflict without recognizing Nagorno-Karabakh as a 
party to it. Azerbaijan's refusal to do so is "the main 
stumbling block," he said. No ceasefire agreement reached 
without Nagorno-Karabakh's participation would provide any 
guarantees, he said. 
  Shumeyko expressed support for the proposal to send a CIS 
peacekeeping force to the conflict zone, the embattled enclave 
being part of the Commonwealth, but said he could see no logic 
behind the idea of involving international forces in CIS to 
conflicts. 
  Armenian negotiator Ararktsian said it was "difficult to 
imagine" that the problem could be solved without the use of 
peacekeepers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

