<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nonrecognition of Karabakh Side at Talks Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nonrecognition of Karabakh Side at Talks Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0505195694 Baku Azerbaycan Radio Televiziyasi Television 
Network in Azeri 1600 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0505195694 </F>
<F P=104>  Baku Azerbaycan Radio Televiziyasi Television 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Azeri </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Qullu Muherremov] </F>
  [Text] Despite the conflicting media reports from Bishkek, 
it is clear that the CIS interparliamentary assembly insists at 
all costs on the recognition of Daghlyk-Karabakh 
[Nagorno-Karabakh] as one of the independent sides in this 
conflict. The elevation of the Karabakh Armenians, who at 
present have no status at all, to prominence at the Bishkek 
meeting shows that the talks are being basically conducted to 
put pressure on Azerbaijan. The course of the developments also 
shows that Armenia, which avoids heeding the CSCE mission, is 
trying to solve the problem speedily and within the CIS 
framework at every opportunity and at all costs. 
  The sudden recognition of Daghlyk-Karabakh as a conflicting 
side by Azerbaijan might place the Republic, which has been 
waging a war with Armenia for years now, in an inextricable 
position. Such a step would not only tie Azerbaijan's hands 
militarily and politically, but might also impede the proper 
understanding of the nature of this war at the international 
level. This is because at the initial stages of the problem, 
when talks were being held to put an end to war under the CSCE 
mandate, Armenia and Azerbaijan took part as sides in the 
conflict and representatives of the Armenian and Azerbaijani 
communities of Daghlyk-Karabakh participated as observers. 
  Why can Azerbaijan not recognize Daghlyk-Karabakh as an 
independent side in the conflict? Because such recognition 
would in practice mean the recognition of the existence of the 
Daghlyk-Karabakh army, regardless of Karabakh's future status. 
This could have grave consequences in the future. Also, such 
recognition on the eve of the Minsk conference would mean 
prematurely determining various parameters for the status of 
Daghlyk-Karabakh. And this will eventually entail further 
concessions. Most important, the recognition of 
Daghlyk-Karabakh as an independent side in the conflict aims at 
providing insurance for the aggressor Armenia. Naturally, the 
CIS states, primarily Russia, are only trying to shield Armenia. 
And the Azerbaijani side's resistance to that approach at 
Bishkek would most likely have a bearing on the situation on the 
front lines in the near future. However, regardless of the fact 
that the aggressor is not being identified at the present time, 
the changing atmosphere in the world will probably not allow the 
aggressor to remain in the shadows indefinitely. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61381 </DOCNO>
