<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grishin Reports Criticism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grishin Reports Criticism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505163094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1320 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Thursday sitting of the Russian Government 
recognized that ministries and departments do not satisfactorily 
fulfill instructions of the Cabinet of Ministers and the 
president. This issue was being considered behind the closed 
doors. 
  The first deputy head of the cabinet's press service Valeriy 
Grishin reported to journalists that the premier sharply 
criticized federal ministries and departments "in stringent 
tones" due to the fact that they do not fulfill instructions of 
the president and the government and underlined that he "would 
not let any delays in fulfillment of instructions." 
  In Grishin's words, the worst executive discipline is within 
the Economics and Finance Ministries, and in the State Property 
Committee which have not fulfilled the greatest number of 
instructions. 
  Sources close to the Cabinet told Interfax that the 
following 
data were mentioned at the sitting: As of May 1, ministries and 
departments have completely fulfilled 156 of 296 instructions, 
six have not been fulfilled at all and the rest are on the 
preparation stage. 
  The government has recommended to release one of the deputy 
chairman of the State Property Committee from his post and two 
deputies Ministers, their names are not being voiced yet. 
  High-ranking employees, including leaders of several 
departments in the government have received severe reprimands 
and warnings. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

