<H3> <TI>   Security Council Official on Current Functions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Council Official on Current Functions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505191294 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0505191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by correspondent A. Sladkov; from the "Vesti" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] In the range of problems connected with insuring our 
country's security, the main question is the protection of 
Russia's present borders. This view was expressed by Valeriy 
Manilov, deputy secretary of the Russian Security Council, at a 
meeting with journalists today. 
  Preserving Russia's unique scientific and 
military-scientific 
technology, halting the outflow of intellectual and scientific 
potential to the West, stabilizing Russian policy in the Asia- 
Pacific region, and solving the problem of the Black Sea Fleet 
should become equally important areas of the Security Council's 
work, Valeriy Manilov said. 
  The increasingly unstable economy is a source of 
considerable 
danger for the country, Valeriy Manilov believes. The Security 
Council intends to play a special role in the further 
establishment of Russian political links with the United States 
and the countries of Western Europe. The first step is the 
prompt examination of options for Russia's entry to the 
Partnership for Peace program. 
  [Begin Manilov recording] There is a pressing need to 
consider all the consequences and results of joining, and above 
all, to take account of Russia's status as a great power by 
definition. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

