<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Print Media To Get Further R64 Billion `To Survive' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Print Media To Get Further R64 Billion `To Survive' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0605093094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 6 May 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> MK0605093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Valeriy Davydov report in the "Press" column: "The Minimum </F>
Task Is To Survive. The Russian Press Committee Is Fully Aware 
of This"] 
  [Excerpt] It has been decided to allocate an additional 64 
billion rubles in subsidies to the Russian press before the end 
of 1994. This was announced at a press conference in the 
Russian Press Committee. Asked where this money will go, 
Committee Deputy Chairman Sergey Gryzunov said that this will be 
decided by a subsidy distribution commission that will include 
journalists, politicians, and government officials. A priority 
right "to survive" will be given to publications which, by the 
committee's recognition, have "a worldwide reputation." 
  It was stated unequivocally that the issue today is 
precisely 
survival. The press is in such a condition that it needs a 
trillion rubles only in subsidies! Such funds, it was said, are 
unavailable. 
  Yet the Press Committee does not see the fact that 
newspapers 
are dying as anything tragic: After all, factories and mines 
are also dying! The only thing that really bothers it is the 
authorities' cynical attitude to books and the press. They, in 
Mr. Gryzunov's expression, have been put next to vodka and 
tobacco. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

