<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic &amp; Social Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Give Up Centralized Grain Imports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Give Up Centralized Grain Imports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505191794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1805 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the moment, Russia is sufficiently provided with 
grain to enable it to give up centralized grain imports, Russian 
Vice Prime Minister Aleksandr Zaveryukha told a news conference 
in Moscow Thursday. 
  Zaveryukha dismissed reports in the Western media of 
projected purchases of grain in the USA saying no talks had been 
held on this issue. 
  According to his information, enterprises of 
Roskhleboprodukt 
stored 17 million tons of grain, while another 1.5 million tons 
may be purchased from domestic farmers. Therefore, given a 
monthly consumption of 2.8 million tons, the stocks will last 
for six months. 
  Zaveryukha pointed out that the minimum purchases of grain 
would be made only for Russia's northern most regions and the 
Far East due to a high cost of shipping grain to the regions 
from Central Russia. However, these purchases, which have 
already amounted to about 200,000 tonnes, will be made 
exclusively on a commercial basis, without state participation. 
  Moreover, Russia has already exported three million tons of 
last year's grain to neighboring republics. 
  Zaveryukha established the fact that given average harvests 
of 100 million tons Russia was quite capable of providing itself 
with grain. At the same time, he refrained from prognosticating 
about the future harvest, because "much would depend on weather 
conditions." 
  Over recent years, Russia has traditionally imported grain. 
In 1992, as many as 26 million tons were delivered to Russia, 
while in 1993 grain imports exceeded 10 million tons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61405 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov088_b_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic &amp; Social Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Premier on Most Difficult Stage of Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Premier on Most Difficult Stage of Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0605092794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0834 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0605092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 6 TASS -- "The Russian economy has 
embarked upon the most difficult stage of reforms. We must see 
that they bring sprouts of revitalisation and not new sufferings 
to the country," First Vice-Premier Oleg Soskovets told the 
newspaper "ROSSIA". His interview is published in today's issue 
of the daily. 
  Soskovets said that the government had begun to determine 
what projects should be supported from the budget. It was 
decided to render government support to the coal industry. It 
is to get from the budget 3.4 trillion roubles in the first six 
months of this year. A decision was also adopted to settle in 
the first quarter of this year the mutual debts of several 
enterprises of the defence industry, the agro-industrial sector, 
and the fuel and energy complex. Quotas were fixed for the 
export of strategic raw materials, as well as customs duties for 
imported goods. A list of federal programmes that are to be 
financed from the budget this year was drawn up. All but ready 
are proposals to effect state control over railway fares and 
over the cost of electric and thermal energy. "Not all the 
measures can be regarded as 100 per cent market oriented, but 
the government is compelled to take them," Soskovets stresses. 
  "In spite of some successes, the economic situation remains 
unstable," he notes. "Crisis phenomena were not stemmed last 
year. The situation in the first quarter of this year is 
characterised by the continuing industrial slump, shrinking 
capital investments, accompanied by the growth of prices for 
factory-made products and consumer goods." 
  "The steps taken by the government are still not yielding 
the 
expected results," Soskovets states. At the same time, he 
stresses that "market relations are gaining strength in the 
Russian economy and measures are being taken to reduce the 
social burden of the transition period. Steps were taken to 
curb the inflation. The process of privatisation is proceeding 
quite dynamically. The non- state sector of economy is gaining 
momentum. The investment decline was slowed down. The consumer 
market is being restored. The country's foreign trade balance 
is favourable." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61406 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov088_b_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic &amp; Social Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Health Statistics Show Growth of `Sick Generation' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Health Statistics Show Growth of `Sick Generation' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0605014794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1515 
GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0605014794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Liliya Luznetsova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 5 May -- The extremely poor state of the 
nation's health is indicated by the infant mortality level. 
Over the last three years a constant increase in the number of 
children not surviving their first year of life has been 
observed in Russia. 
  Whereas in 1990 an average of 17.4 babies per 1,000 births 
were dying, the figure became 17.8 in 1992, 18 in 1993, and 19 a 
year later. 
  These figures from the Russian Federation's national report 
to the eighth world conference on the situation of women, which 
is to be held in Beijing next year, are capable of shocking 
medical specialists throughout the world -- which is not 
surprising since in the advanced countries the figure for baby 
mortality in recent years has not only not increased, but has 
indeed decreased and stabilized at a level of five to eight 
deaths of children in their first year per 1,000 births. 
  According to statistics there has been a deterioration too 
in 
the health of babies. Whereas three years ago one in seven 
babies were born ill or became ill, the figure rose in the 
following year to one in six, and a year later it was one in 
five. 
  A steady increase in illness among children below the age of 
14 years has also been noted. Our children are particularly 
suffering from illnesses affecting the organs of the respiratory 
tract, the alimentary tract, and the nervous system. 
  The number of congenital deformities and development defects 
is also growing. The number of such defects per 1,000 people 
has increased by over 28 percent, while the number of tumors in 
children has risen by almost a quarter. 
  The appearance of a "sick generation" of Russians is shown 
by 
the fact that child invalids alone in the country (by WHO 
estimates) now number hundreds of thousands. In the pre-school 
age group, 15-20 percent of children are suffering chronic 
illnesses, and by the time they leave school almost half of the 
children are limited in their choice of vocation by the state of 
their health. Specialists claim that only one tenth of Russian 
schoolchildren are in practice healthy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

