<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Explosions Moratorium To Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Explosions Moratorium To Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505162194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1359 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow May 5 TASS -- [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic 
correspondents Boris Krivoshey and Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Russia intends to continue the moratorium on nuclear 
explosions with the aim of securing favorable conditions and 
political support for conducting multilateral talks on working 
out a treaty on the comprehensive nuclear test ban, Russian 
Foreign Ministry spokesman Grigoriy Karasin told a briefing here 
today. 
  Commenting on the second round of these talks due to begin 
within the framework of the disarmament conference in Geneva on 
May 16, Grigoriy Karasin stressed that the treaty to be worked 
out was not only a means for the strengthening of the nuclear 
non-proliferation regime but also the important step towards the 
furtherance of strategic stability. 
  The Russian side regards work on this treaty as a "priority 
direction in the activities of the disarmament conference in 
1994", the Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman told journalists. 
  According to Grigoriy Karasin, at the forthcoming meeting 
Russia will seek to "intensify multilateral talks with the aim 
of preparing a treaty, possibly by the spring of 1995 which 
would considerably promote the success of the oncoming 
conference devoted to the prolongation of the Nuclear 
Non-proliferation Treaty scheduled for this period". 

</TEXT>

