<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament To Ratify Agreement on Free Trade Zones </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament To Ratify Agreement on Free Trade Zones </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505164994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1519 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 5 TASS -- The Russian parliament is 
preparing to ratify an agreement on the creation of free trade 
zones signed by heads of state and governments of the 
Commonwealth countries, Vladimir Meshcheryakov, deputy chairman 
of the state customs committee of the Russian Federation, told 
BUSINESS-TASS. 
  According to Vladimir Meshcheryakov, the Federation Council 
plans to hold hearings on the preparation for ratification of 
this package of documents on May 16. 
  The signing of the agreement on the establishment of free 
trade zones, the deputy chairman of the state customs committee 
noted, is the first stage in the process of economic drawing 
together of the Commonwealth countries. The second stage will 
mark the transition to a customs union. 
  In both cases, Vladimir Meshcheryakov explained, there will 
be no quantitative and tariff restrictions in mutual trade but 
the existence of free trade zones does not prevent the state 
from the independent determination of its foreign economic 
policy. After all, a customs union is first of all common 
customs tariffs. 
  Vladimir Meshcheryakov paid attention to the fact that a 
concept of free trade in the Commonwealth is not applied in a 
pure form now. In practice the so-called exceptions from the 
free trade regime are employed which were legalized by bilateral 
agreements between Russia and other Commonwealth countries 
signed in 1992-1993. 
  These exceptions concern export tariffs, quotas and 
licenses. 
For this reason the agreement signed by leaders of the 
Commonwealth countries on April 15 is considerably advancing the 
Commonwealth towards the establishment of a customs union, 
Vladimir Meshcheryakov pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61418 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov088_c_94004" </HT>


