<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Official: New Stage of U.S.-Ukrainian Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Official: New Stage of U.S.-Ukrainian Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505214294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2006 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UKRINFORM correspondent Aleksey Trotsenko for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Kiev 5 May TASS -- We have entered another, more 
positive stage of our cooperation, according to Nicholas Burns, 
senior director of the U.S. National Security Council and an 
adviser to President Bill Clinton. 
  Burns heads a U.S. economic delegation, which arrived in 
Kiev 
a few days ago for talks with Ukrainian officials on how to 
apply $350 million in aid. 
  On Thursday, Burns met Ukrainian Parliament Chairman Ivan 
Plyushch. The speaker informed the American guest about the 
current situation in the former Soviet Republic. He described 
the visit by such a representative delegation as another step 
towards further development of mutually beneficial partnership 
between the two countries. The United States can contribute 
considerably to solution of problems currently facing Ukraine, 
Plyushch stressed. 
  Burns said the present visit had been mostly focused on 
exchange of opinions about economic cooperation between the 
United States and Ukraine. This issue was tackled during 
meetings with Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk and government 
ministers. 
  According to the U.S. official, President Clinton believes 
the two countries entered a new stage of bilateral relations. 
The previous stage concentrated on dismantling of Ukraine's 
nuclear weapons inherited from the former Soviet Union. At 
present, the emphasis is laid on closer and more extensive 
economic ties. "To the United States, Ukraine is seen as one of 
the most important countries in Europe," Burns said. 
  He insisted the former Soviet republic speed up economic 
reform if it wanted more aid in future. "The Ukrainian 
Government and parliament and the society at large want to 
achieve economic reform. But we believe the progress has 
Gorbachev to go further. Much greater progress has to be made," 
Burns told a news conference. 
  The U.S. delegation head called on ministers to move more 
quickly in implementing an ambitious privatization programme and 
creating a better climate for trade. 
  "The United States would like to lead an international 
effort 
to provide help to Ukraine with its economic reform programme," 
he pointed out. The combined sum pledged by the U.S. to the 
newly-independent state puts Ukraine behind only Israel, Egypt, 
and Russia in terms of U.S. foreign aid. 
  Among other projects, the United States will print 
privatization certificates to be issued to all Ukrainian 
citizens in July and set up an enterprise fund to give loans to 
small businesses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

