<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-7 Experts Says Chernobyl Should be Closed Down </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    G-7 Experts Says Chernobyl Should be Closed Down </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505163194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1424 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UKRINFORM correspondent Aleksandr Litvinov for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Kiev 5 May TASS -- Ukraine should have made great 
contribution to environmental security in Europe, if it closed 
down the Chernobyl nuclear power plant. 
  Such was the position which visiting representatives of the 
G-7 countries expressed at a meeting with Yuriy Kostenko, 
Ukrainian minister for environmental protection, on Thursday [5 
May]. 
  If the Chernobyl nuclear power plant keeps on functioning, 
it 
will thus pose a permanent threat not only to Ukraine, but also 
to other countries of the world, they emphasized. 
  According to Kostenko, his ministry has always been the only 
state body to consistently demand that the Chernobyl nuclear 
power plant be closed down as soon as possible. 
  The measures, which are being taken now to reinforce the 
plant's security, will hardly suffice to prevent radioactive 
pollution of the area in case of another accident, he said. 
  Representatives of the so-called "pro-nuclear" lobby, who 
exercise much influence at all levels of power throughout the 
Commonwealth of Independent States, put up a most fierce 
resistance, he explained. They insist on a constant build-up in 
nuclear capacities, gambling on the fact that Ukraine has now to 
face the problem of insufficient power supplies. 

</TEXT>

