<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities Lift State of Emergency in Almaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Authorities Lift State of Emergency in Almaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505123494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1028 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The state of emergency declared in Kazakhstan's 
capital Almaty on April 29 due to the shortage of fuel was 
lifted on 4 May. As the Deputy Mayor Yakov Zayts, who leads a 
commission on emergencies, has told INTERFAX, there was fuel 
rationing in the city on 29 April for all enterprises and 
organizations not involved in vital urban services. 
  In his words, the city's administration were forced to take 
extreme measures because of poor oil supply, slashed because of 
the consumer debt. He reported that the debts had been 
partially repaid at the expense of credits. According to his 
information, a number of state oil refineries have already sent 
about 3000 tonnes of gasoline to Almaty. He noted that "a small 
fuel reserve" has been created in the city, and "the situation 
is returning to normal." 

</TEXT>

