<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Launches Offensive Fearing Breach of Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Launches Offensive Fearing Breach of Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0505103094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 May 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0505103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Igor Rotar under "Tajikistan" rubric: "More </F>
Casualties on Tajik-Afghan Border. Opposition Seems To Have 
Launched Big Offensive"] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] To all appearances, a new 
sharp spiral in the escalation of tensions in Tajikistan is in 
the cards. According to information received from sources close 
to opposition leaders, as many as six Russian border guards, not 
one, were killed in the recent clash along the Tajik border, and 
eight were wounded with two of them being in serious condition. 
The opposition contend that their like-minded associates were 
firing from Tajik territory. According to information from the 
same source, Tajik militants are arriving in great numbers from 
Afghanistan in the Pamirs. Tajik opposition members who live in 
Moscow cannot clearly explain what is happening in their own 
country because communications with their associates from 
Afghanistan have been broken. They think, however, that leaders 
of the Islamic Movement of Tajikistan in Afghanistan have 
decided that Dushanbe has breached the understanding reached 
with the opposition by starting to discuss a new constitution 
before the second round of talks, and has clearly gambled on a 
military solution of the question. Your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 
correspondent has come to learn that Tajikistan leaders have 
been urgently summoned to Moscow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61461 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov088_m_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Pushes for Single Monetary System With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Pushes for Single Monetary System With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505124894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1125 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe 5 May TASS -- One of the main objectives of 
the current visit to Moscow of the state and government 
delegation from Tajikistan, led by the Republic's leader Emomali 
Rakhmonov is to convince Moscow that it is necessary to speed up 
the process of unification of the monetary systems of Russia and 
Tajikistan, a ranking source in the Tajik Government told 
ITAR-TASS. 
  The Tajik delegation includes Prime Minister Abdudzhalil 
Samadov, Foreign Minister Rashid Olimov, National Bank Chairman 
Kayum Kavmidinov and a large group of experts. According to an 
official version, set forth by Emomali Rakhmonov's press 
secretary Nabi Karimov, the deepening and expansion of bilateral 
political, economic, and military cooperation will be discussed 
with the Russian leadership in Moscow. 
  A Tajik Government official said any further procrastination 
on the process of unification of the monetary systems can lead 
to unpredictable political and economic consequences, since the 
industrial production slump has already reached a critical point 
because of blocked payments and the majority of the population 
have not received pay packets and various social allowances 
since the beginning of the year. 
  Asked whether Tajikistan was planning to introduce temporary 
banknotes for the duration of the transitional period, as 
announced by the prime minister at recent press conference, the 
government official said there was no uniform approach to the 
problem among the Republics leaders. Moreover, Emomali 
Rakhmonov and National Bank Chairman Kayum Kavmidinov are 
against this measure. According to the official the Tajik 
leader will ask Moscow for more Russian cash to last through the 
transition period. 
  Russian journalists at Dushanbe airport were denied even a 
blitz interview with the republic's top leaders before their 
departure for Moscow. Prime Minister Abdudzhalil Samadov said 
all details of the visit will be released to journalists after 
the visit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

