<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev To Outline Partnership Proposals in Brussels </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev To Outline Partnership Proposals in Brussels </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0605130394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1124 
GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0605130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov and Mikhail </F>
Shevtsov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 6 May (ITAR-TASS) -- Russian Federation 
Defense Minister Army General Pavel Grachev plans to outline 
Russia's new approaches to the "Partnership for Peace" program 
in Brussels on 24 May. He stated this at a news conference at 
the Russian Defense Ministry today. 
  In his words, Russia should put out its own idea of 
partnership. Before 15 May a group of Russian scientists should 
draw up proposals on this issue, they will be then examined at a 
meeting of the Security Council. If they are approved, the 
Russian proposals will be announced to NATO defense ministers by 
Pavel Grachev at the NATO headquarters. 
  The minister said that what is proposed in the "Partnership 
for Peace" program does not entirely suit Russia. "The role of 
NATO and the West European Union is increasing, but they do not 
have the right to substitute the peacekeeping functions of the 
CSCE and ignore Russia's interests," Pavel Grachev believes. 
  Pavel Grachev also said that he discussed issues relating to 
Russia's new proposals to the "Partnership for Peace" program 
with Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

